WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6 New Year's English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
And I'm Beth. It seems people around the world are in love with snacks

5
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
From old favourites like popcorn and crisps

6
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
To new inventions like the chocolate sandwich

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Snacks are big business

8
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
With an estimated $1.5 trillion a year spent globally on snacking

9
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Let's listen as British food historian Annie Gray

10
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
An Argentinian chef Barbara O'yavari

11
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Tell BBC World Service program the food chain

12
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
What they like to snack on between meals

13
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
I like salted peanuts

14
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And I love a banana

15
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Preferably together actually I find that they hit the spot

16
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
My favourite snack is called Chippa

17
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Is a small round bun made with cassava cheese, butter, milk and salt

18
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Barbara's favourite snack is a cheese bread called Chippa

19
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
While for Annie it's the combination of peanuts and banana

20
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.000
That hits the spot and idiom meaning that it's exactly what you want

21
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Neil, what's your favourite snack?

22
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Well, I want to say something healthy but actually, you know, I really love a bag of crisps

23
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Ah, me too, yeah crisps are good

24
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Well, whatever you like to number on in this episode

25
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
We'll find out why we are so in love with snack food

26
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
As usual, we'll learn some useful new words and phrases

27
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
And remember, you'll find all the vocabulary and a quiz on our website

28
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

29
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Okay, but first I have a question for you, Beth

30
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
According to a recent Yugav survey

31
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Which of the following snacks is most popular amongst Brits

32
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Is it a crisps, b, confectionery and chocolate

33
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Or c, savoury snacks and biscuits?

34
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
Well, we both just said crisps, so I'm going to say crisps

35
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Well, we'll find out the answer later in the program

36
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Someone with a professional interest in snacking is Christine Corkron

37
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
President of snack international

38
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
The trade association for the industry

39
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Here, Christine shares her ideas about why we love to snack

40
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
With BBC World Service program The Food Chain

41
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
A snack is an affordable luxury

42
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
So if you've had a bad day or money is tight

43
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
This is something that you can turn to

44
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And I think that is why you see it as so popular

45
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Consumers, especially in the United States

46
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Are looking for smaller, more convenient portions

47
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
They're not always going to be able to sit down and have three meals a day

48
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Right?

49
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:46.000
So they're eating on the go-to

50
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And the other thing that you see is this desire for very specific functional ingredients

51
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Right?

52
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
So mental clarity, gut health, muscle development, these sorts of things

53
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Again, they're nicely packaged in snack sizes

54
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Snacks are often seen as a little luxury

55
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
But to be successful, a snack must also be affordable

56
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
An adjective meaning not expensive

57
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Snacks which are cheap enough for most people to buy

58
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Will sell even if money is tight

59
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
A phrase used to describe a situation where there's only just enough money to live on

60
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Thanks to Snacks, today few of people sit down to eat a proper meal

61
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Instead they eat on the go

62
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
If you do something on the go, you do it while you're busy travelling

63
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Or moving around rather than at home

64
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Many modern snacks target a specific function

65
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
For example, an energy drink might claim to improve your gut health or your mental clarity

66
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
A term describing a state of mind which is focused and engaged

67
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Not dull or foggy

68
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
But not everyone is a fan of modern packaged snacks

69
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Such as the bag of crisps and chocolate bars which fill our shops

70
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Originally from Argentina, Barbara or Yavari

71
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Now lives in Florida, USA

72
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Here, Barbara tells BBC World Services the food chain

73
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
How she encourages her nine-year-old son to choose more natural snacks

74
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Personally, I enjoy cooking and eating more natural, simpler snacks

75
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
But of course, I can't swim against the current and if my nine-year-old wants to eat

76
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:24.000
The little baked snacks that have cheddar

77
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Ironically, it is something baked with cheese in it

78
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Which is similar to what I enjoy, it's just the modern twist

79
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Barbara wants her son to eat healthy, homemade food

80
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Although he prefers modern packaged snacks

81
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Barbara complains she can't swim against the current

82
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
The idioms swim against the current means to act differently from other people

83
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Often because you do not mind being different

84
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Well, Neil, all these snacks have made me hungry

85
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Now isn't it time to reveal the answer to your question?

86
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Yes, it is. I asked according to a recent U-Gov survey

87
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Which of the following snacks is the most popular amongst breads, crisps,

88
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Confectionary and chocolate or savory snacks and biscuits and the answer was

89
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
B, Confectionary and Chocolate

90
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Which 45% of Britain's indulging weekly according to that survey

91
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned

92
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Starting with the phrase hits the spot

93
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Which describes something which is exactly what you want or need

94
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If something is affordable, it's cheap enough that most people have enough money to buy it

95
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
The phrase money is tight means you only have just enough money to live

96
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
The idiom on the go means doing things while you're busy traveling or moving around

97
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Mental clarity is a state in which your mind is fully focused and active

98
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Not dull or foggy

99
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And finally, people who swim against the current or the tide

100
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Do or say things differently from most other people

101
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Once again, our six minutes are up

102
00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
But why not head over to our website

103
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:04.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com to try the quiz and work sheets for this episode

104
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
See you again soon!

105
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Goodbye!
